br.ufrgs.MASBench.BinaryMaxSum.Factor

Class StandardFactor<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • br.ufrgs.MASBench.BinaryMaxSum.Factor.AbstractFactor<T>
      • br.ufrgs.MASBench.BinaryMaxSum.Factor.StandardFactor<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - Type of the factor's identity.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Factor<T>

    public class StandardFactor<T>
extends AbstractFactor<T>
    Implementation of a standard (binary) max-sum factor.
    The potential of this factor is represented as an array of costs/utilities, where the list array a cost/utility for each combination of values in the list of neighbors. For example, an array [0, 2, 3, 6, 3, 4, 5, 8] represents the cost/utility table defined below, where x, y, and z are the three neighbors of this factor: 
     | x | y | z | Cost
 ---------------------
 | 0 | 0 | 0 |  0
 | 0 | 0 | 1 |  2
 | 0 | 1 | 0 |  3
 | 0 | 1 | 1 |  6
 | 1 | 0 | 0 |  3
 | 1 | 0 | 1 |  4
 | 1 | 1 | 0 |  5
 | 1 | 1 | 1 |  8
    You must ensure that there are exactly 2**len(neighbors) costs/utilities in the potential array.
    Author:
    Marc Pujol (mpujol @ iiia.csic.es)
